00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:17.950
Well, let's think about this.

00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:22.640
If I have a 1 and a 5,
that's going to add up to 6.

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:24.650
In this entire column,
that's the only way

00:02:24.650 --> 00:02:26.320
that I add up to 6.

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:28.260
Right over here, let's see.

00:02:28.260 --> 00:02:31.550
If I have a 2 on the black
die, then I'm going to need a 4

00:02:31.550 --> 00:02:34.410
on the white die to add up to 6.

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:36.620
If I have a 3 on the black
die, I'm going to need a 3

00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:38.572
on the white die to add up to 6.

00:02:38.572 --> 00:02:40.780
If I have a 4 on the black
die, I'm going to need a 2

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:41.990
on the white die.

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:44.550
If I have a 5 on the black
die, I'm going to need a 1

00:02:44.550 --> 00:02:45.620
on the white die.

00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:47.370
And then if I have 6
six on the black die,

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:50.190
it's actually impossible that
the sum will be exactly 6.

00:02:50.190 --> 00:02:51.790
So there's no zero
on the white die.

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:54.510
So none of these
meet the constraint.

00:02:54.510 --> 00:02:58.790
So here I have one, two,
three, four, five possibilities

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:01.060
where my dice add up to 6.

00:03:01.060 --> 00:03:03.620
So I have five
possibilities out of a total

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:06.070
of 36 equally likely ones.

00:03:06.070 --> 00:03:07.950
This is a six by
six grid, and it

00:03:07.950 --> 00:03:09.490
comes from six
possibilities for one

00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:12.120
die times six possibilities
for the other die.

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:14.690
So 5 possibilities
satisfy my constraint

00:03:14.690 --> 00:03:18.371
out of a total of 36.

